{"CodeSource":"using UnityEngine;\r\nusing System.Collections;\r\nusing System.Collections.Generic;\r\n\r\npublic class FirePlayerLaser : MonoBehaviour\r\n{\r\n    [HideMember]\r\n    // HIDEN\r\n    public void Awake()\r\n    {\r\n        Step.ChangeStep += (sender, e) =>\r\n        {\r\n            var lasers = FindObjectsOfType<MovePlayerLaser>();\r\n\r\n            foreach (var laser in lasers)\r\n            {\r\n                if (laser.transform.parent == null)\r\n                {\r\n                    Destroy(laser.gameObject);\r\n                }\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    [DeclareMemberStep(Steps.DeclareLaserVariable)]\r\n    // When the user hits the Space key, we want to create a laser,\r\n    // but first we need to have a laser prefab that we can copy.\r\n    // \r\n    // We will need to declare a variable that will hold the Laser Prefab to copy. \r\n    //  \r\n    // Declare a variable to store the laser gameObject called \"laserPrefab\". \r\n\r\n    // OBJECTIVE: Create the <laserPrefab> Variable\r\n\r\n    // The <laserPrefab> is a <GameObject> that we will use as a template to create new laser objects.\r\n\r\n    // Now we have a variable that will store the laser prefab gameObject, but we have not used it yet.\r\n    public GameObject laserPrefab;\r\n\r\n    void Update()\r\n    {\r\n        if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.IfSpaceKeyHit)) { return; }\r\n\r\n        // We need to create a laser projectile for the player. \r\n        // When the user presses the space key a laser will shoot out from the Player position.\r\n        //\r\n        // To check for a single key press Input, we need to use the GetKeyDown method.\r\n        // Also, we need to indicate the key to get which is the Space key.\r\n        //\r\n        // Check if the user has pressed the Space key using the GetKeyDown method and the Space KeyCode.\r\n\r\n        // OBJECTIVE: Check if the Player Hit the Space key\r\n        // SEARCH: space key\r\n        // DOCS: http://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Input.GetKeyDown.html\r\n\r\n        // The <GetKeyDown> method tells us when the user first presses a key.\r\n        // We will check if the <Space> key has been pressed down.\r\n        // The <KeyCode> enumeration contains a list of all possible Key names.\r\n\r\n        // Now we can handle if the user hits the Space key.\r\n        // However, we don't do anything yet so it looks the same.\r\n        var __keyCode = KeyCode.Space;\r\n\r\n        if (Step.IsExperimentingAt(Steps.InstantiateLaser))\r\n        {\r\n            __keyCode = Step.ExperimentWith(__keyCode,\r\n                        KeyCode.Space, \"KeyCode.Space\",\r\n                        KeyCode.Return, \"KeyCode.Return\",\r\n                        KeyCode.LeftAlt, \"KeyCode.LeftAlt\",\r\n                        KeyCode.LeftControl, \"KeyCode.LeftControl\",\r\n                        KeyCode.X, \"KeyCode.X\");\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        var wasSpaceHit = Input.GetKeyDown(__keyCode);\r\n\r\n        if (wasSpaceHit)\r\n        {\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.InstantiateLaser)) { return; }\r\n\r\n            // Now we have the laserPrefab that we can copy.\r\n            //\r\n            // We need to use it to create new lasers when the space key is hit.\r\n            //\r\n            // We must use a method called Instantiate to clone the laserPrefab and create a new laser.\r\n            // We must give the Instantiate method three values:\r\n            //\r\n            // First we pass the object to clone.\r\n            // Second we pass the position for the new object. \r\n            // Third we pass the rotation of the new object.\r\n            //\r\n            // We will use the players current position for the new laser,\r\n            // and we will use the default rotation which is called \"Quaternion.identity\".\r\n            //\r\n            // Let's try to Instantiate a laser from the players position with the identity Quaternion.\r\n\r\n            // OBJECTIVE: Instantiate the laserPrefab at the player's position.\r\n            // SEARCH: instantiate\r\n            // DOCS: http://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Object.Instantiate.html\r\n\r\n            // The <Instantiate> method clones a gameObject.\r\n            // We want to clone the <laserPrefab> to create a new laser.\r\n            // We want the new laser to start at the player's <position> which we get from the player's <transform> component.\r\n            // We do not need to rotate the laser, so we use the <identity> property of the <Quaternion> class, which means it will have no rotation.\r\n\r\n            // Now our player will fire a laser, but the laser doesn't move yet.\r\n            // [Hit the space key to fire a laser. Move the ship around to see it better.]\r\n            Instantiate(laserPrefab, transform.position, Quaternion.identity);\r\n        }\r\n {"CodeSource":"using System.Collections;\r\nusing UnityEngine;\r\n\r\n\r\npublic class MovePlayer : MonoBehaviour\r\n{\r\n    [HideMember]\r\n    // HIDEN\r\n    void Awake()\r\n    {\r\n        Step.ChangeStep += (sender, e) =>\r\n        {\r\n            transform.position = new Vector3();\r\n        };\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    [DeclareMemberStep(Steps.DeclarePlayerControllerSpeed)]\r\n    // Now our player is always moving at a constant speed.\r\n    // Instead, we want to be able to change the speed from the Unity Editor to make it just right for the game play.\r\n    //\r\n    // A value that can be changed is called a \"variable\".\r\n    // To create a variable, we must declare it, which means we must give it a type and a name.\r\n    // For our purpose, we need a \"float\" type that is called \"playerSpeed\". \r\n    //\r\n    // Also, we need to make a variable that can be modified in the Unity Editor.\r\n    // To do this, we must declare the variable in our script and add the \"public\" keyword.\r\n    // This will tell C# that the variable is accessible to other code and let Unity access it.\r\n    //\r\n    // With this, we will be able to change our variable's value in Unity and use that value in our Translate call.\r\n    // \r\n    // Let's declare a public float called \"playerSpeed\" with the default value of \"5f\".\r\n\r\n    // OBJECTIVE: Declare a <playerSpeed> variable with default of <5f>.\r\n\r\n    // The default <playerSpeed> is <5f> meters per second.\r\n\r\n    // Now we have a speed variable with a value of 5f.\r\n    // We are not using this yet, so it does not change what we see.\r\n    public float playerSpeed = 5f;\r\n\r\n    void Update()\r\n    {\r\n        using (var step = Step.CreateStepContext(\r\n            Steps.TranslateLeftAndRight_WithRightOnly,\r\n            Steps.TranslateLeftAndRight_MoveRightOverTime,\r\n            Steps.TranslateLeftAndRight_MoveRightWithTimeAndSpeedConstant,\r\n            Steps.TranslateLeftAndRight_MoveRightWithTimeAndSpeedVariable,\r\n            Steps.TranslateLeftAndRight_GetHorizontalInput,\r\n            Steps.TranslateLeftAndRight_UseHorizontalInput,\r\n            Steps.TranslateUpAndDown_GetVerticalInput,\r\n            Steps.TranslateUpAndDown_UseVerticalInput\r\n            ))\r\n        {\r\n            if (step.IsAt(Steps.TranslateLeftAndRight_WithRightOnly))\r\n            {\r\n                // Now that we have a player ship in the game scene, let's make it move.\r\n                //\r\n                // But first, we need to learn some terms to understand how we can control the position of the player ship.\r\n                // Listen carefully, this is long, but it is important...\r\n                //\r\n                // In Unity, every game object has a \"transform\" component.\r\n                // This transform component controls everything about the game object's location in the game scene.\r\n                // The transform controls the \"position\", \"rotation\", and \"scale\" of the game object.\r\n                // For now, we only need to worry about the \"position\".\r\n                //\r\n                // The position is the game object's location in the scene.\r\n                // The position has 3 coordinates: x, y, and z.\r\n                // The x is the side to side position.\r\n                // The y is the up and down position.\r\n                // The z is the distance from the screen (the depth position).\r\n                // \r\n                // These 3 coordinates (x, y, and z) are grouped together into a single value type called a \"Vector3\".\r\n                //\r\n                // Now, To get back to moving the player ship:\r\n                // The easiest way to move our ship is to use the \"Translate\" method.\r\n                // Translate is just a math term that means to move something in a certain direction and distance.\r\n                // \r\n                // So we will use the \"Translate\" method of the \"transform\" to move out player.\r\n                //\r\n                // But we need to tell it which way to move the player.\r\n                // For that, we will use the \"Vector3\" type.\r\n                // The Vector3 type contains some preset values for common directions like \"right\" or \"left\".\r\n                // So, we will use the \"right\" direction to move the player ship to the right.\r\n                //\r\n                // Now, let's try to translate the Player to the right.\r\n\r\n                // OBJECTIVE: Translate the Player to the Right.\r\n                // SEARCH: Transform Translate\r\n                // DOCS: http://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Transform.Translate.html\r\n\r\n                // The <transform> holds the values for a game object's position, rotation, and scale.\r\n                // A simple way to move a game object is by calling the <Translate> method of the <transform>.\r\n                // <Translate> means to move something a certain direction and distance.\r\n                // A <Vector3> is a value type that contains 3 coordinates: x, y, and z.\r\n                // The <Vector3> type contains values for the 6 primary directions which are: <right> and left, up and down, and forward and back.\r\n                // In order to move our object, we can call the <Translate> method of the <transform> component and make it go to the <right>.\r\n\r\n                // Now our player is flying to the right.\r\n                // Notice that immediately the Player flies off the screen to the right. \r\n                var __direction = Vector3.right;\r\n\r\n                if (Step.IsExperimentingHere)\r\n                {\r\n                    __direction = Step.ExperimentWith(__direction,\r\n                        Vector3.right, \"Vector3.right\", Vector3.left, \"Vector3.left\",\r\n                        Vector3.forward, \"Vector3.forward\", Vector3.back, \"Vector3.back\",\r\n                        Vector3.zero, \"Vector3.zero\");\r\n                }\r\n\r\n                transform.Translate(__direction);\r\n            }\r\n\r\n            if (step.IsAt(Steps.TranslateLeftAndRight_MoveRightOverTime))\r\n            {\r\n                // Notice that the player is moving off the screen too quickly.\r\n                // This is because we are moving the player 1 meter to the right every frame.\r\n                // Assuming the frame rate is 60 frames per second, the player is moving 60 meters per second.\r\n                //\r\n                // Instead, we want to move the player a small amount each frame.\r\n                // Then, over time it will move the full amount.\r\n                // \r\n                // This is the purpose of the \"deltaTime\" property.\r\n                // We must multiply the direction by deltaTime, and then the player will move correctly over time (at about 1 meter per second).\r\n                // \r\n                // Note: To deltaTime property is inside the Time class, so we must type \"Time.deltaTime\" to use it.\r\n                //\r\n                // Modify the Translate call to multiply the direction by deltaTime.\r\n\r\n                // OBJECTIVE: Move the Player to the Right Over Time\r\n                // SEARCH: Meters Per Second\r\n                // DOCS: http://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Time-deltaTime.html \r\n\r\n                // We move the player to the <right> over time by using the <deltaTime> property.\r\n                // We should always multiply by <deltaTime> to move an object over time.\r\n                // In order to move our object to the right over time, we can call the <Translate> method of the <transform> component and make it go to the <right> using <deltaTime>.\r\n\r\n                // Now our Player is moving to the right 1 meter per second.\r\n                // Notice that the Player is moving at a much slower pace.\r\n                var __time = Time.deltaTime;\r\n                var __direction = Vector3.right;\r\n\r\n                if (Step.IsExperimentingHere)\r\n                {\r\n                    __time = Step.ExperimentWith(__time,\r\n                        Time.deltaTime, \"Time.deltaTime\", 0.001f, \" 0.001f\", 0.01f, \"0.01f\", 0.1f, \"0.1f\", 1f, \"1f\");\r\n\r\n                    __direction = Step.ExperimentWith(__direction,\r\n                       Vector3.right, \"Vector3.right\", Vector3.left, \"Vector3.left\",\r\n                       Vector3.forward, \"Vector3.forward\", Vector3.back, \"Vector3.back\",\r\n                       Vector3.zero, \"Vector3.zero\");\r\n                }\r\n\r\n                transform.Translate(__direction * __time);\r\n            }\r\n\r\n            if (step.IsAt(Steps.TranslateLeftAndRight_MoveRightWithTimeAndSpeedConstant))\r\n            {\r\n                // Now the Player is moving too slow.\r\n                // We need to include a speed value in our Translate call.\r\n                // For now, let's make the player move 5 meters per second to the right.\r\n                //\r\n                // Before we can enter the code, let me explain how numbers work in C#...\r\n                //\r\n                // In games, most of the numbers have decimal places.\r\n                // For example, we might want our ship to go at half speed, which is 2.5 meters per second.\r\n                // When we use a number that can have a decimal place, it is called a \"float\" (a floating-point number).\r\n                //\r\n                // To tell C# that we want to use a float, we must add an \"f\" to the number.\r\n                // So we will type \"5f\" instead of just \"5\" to tell C# that our number is a float.\r\n                // \r\n                // To include our speed of \"5f\", we need to multiply the direction by \"5f\".\r\n                // \r\n                // Extend the Translate call to multiply the direction by \"5f\".\r\n\r\n                // OBJECTIVE: Move the Player at 5 Meters per Second\r\n\r\n                // We move the player to the <right> at <5> meters per second.\r\n\r\n                // Now our Player is moving to the right 5 meters per second.\r\n                // This is near to the correct speed for the game.\r\n                var __speed = 5f;\r\n                var __direction = Vector3.right;\r\n\r\n                if (Step.IsExperimentingHere)\r\n                {\r\n                    __speed = Step.ExperimentWith(__speed, 5f, 1f, 2f, 10f, 100f, -1f, -5f);\r\n                    __direction = Step.ExperimentWith(__direction,\r\n                        Vector3.right, \"Vector3.right\", Vector3.left, \"Vector3.left\",\r\n                        Vector3.forward, \"Vector3.forward\", Vector3.back, \"Vector3.back\",\r\n                        Vector3.zero, \"Vector3.zero\");\r\n                }\r\n\r\n                transform.Translate(__direction * __speed * Time.deltaTime);\r\n            }\r\n\r\n            if (step.IsAt(Steps.TranslateLeftAndRight_MoveRightWithTimeAndSpeedVariable))\r\n            {\r\n                // Now we need to use the \"playerSpeed\" variable instead of the hard-coded \"5f\".\r\n                //\r\n                // Change the \"5f\" to \"playerSpeed\" in the Translate call.\r\n\r\n                // OBJECTIVE: Use the <playerSpeed> variable in the Translate call.\r\n\r\n                // The player is moving to the <right> at the speed inside the <playerSpeed> variable.\r\n\r\n                // Now our Player is moving to the right according to our speed.\r\n                // This looks the same because the speed is still 5 meters per second.\r\n                var __speed = playerSpeed;\r\n                var __direction = Vector3.right;\r\n\r\n                if (Step.IsExperimentingHere)\r\n                {\r\n                    __speed = Step.ExperimentWith(__speed,\r\n                        playerSpeed, \"playerSpeed\", 5f, \"5f\", 1f, \"1f\", 2f, \"2f\", 10f, \"10f\", 100f, \"100f\", -1f, \"-1f\", -5f, \"-5f\");\r\n                    __direction = Step.ExperimentWith(__direction,\r\n                        Vector3.right, \"Vector3.right\", Vector3.left, \"Vector3.left\",\r\n                        Vector3.forward, \"Vector3.forward\", Vector3.back, \"Vector3.back\",\r\n                        Vector3.zero, \"Vector3.zero\");\r\n                }\r\n\r\n                transform.Translate(__direction * __speed * Time.deltaTime);\r\n            }\r\n\r\n            if (step.IsAt(Steps.TranslateLeftAndRight_GetHorizontalInput))\r\n            {\r\n                // Now we are successfully moving to the right at an acceptable speed,\r\n                // but we still need to allow the user to control the player ship.\r\n                //\r\n                // In order to access the user input, we need to use the Input class.\r\n                // The Input class combines the input from many types of controls like a keyboard, mouse, joystick, or gamepad.\r\n                // It maps the controller values into an named axis that we can access easily.\r\n                //\r\n                // For the left and right movement, we will use the \"Horizontal\" axis.\r\n                // The \"Horizontal\" axis maps to the left and right arrow keys (or A and D for WASD input).\r\n                //\r\n                // Go ahead and try to store the \"Horizontal\" input into a variable named \"horizontalInput\".\r\n\r\n                // OBJECTIVE: Get the <Horizontal> Input value\r\n                // SEARCH: horizontal input\r\n                // DOCS: http://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Input.GetAxis.html\r\n\r\n                // In order to get the user input, we need to use the <Input> class.\r\n                // The <GetAxis> method will return a value between -1 and +1.\r\n                // GetAxis(\"Horizontal\") will return 0.5f if the user pushes the jostick half way to the right, which is a <float> value.\r\n                // The <\"Horizontal\"> axis will be -1 for left input (A key) or +1 for right input (D key).\r\n                // The <horizontalInput> now holds the left and right input value.\r\n\r\n                // Now we have the left and right user input.\r\n                // However, we have not used it yet, so it still looks the same.\r\n                float horizontalInput = Input.GetAxis(\"Horizontal\");\r\n\r\n                transform.Translate(Vector3.right * playerSpeed * Time.deltaTime);\r\n            }\r\n\r\n            if (step.IsAt(Steps.TranslateLeftAndRight_UseHorizontalInput))\r\n            {\r\n                // Now we have a variable that holds the value of the key we pressed.\r\n                // We need to use that variable to control the player movement.\r\n                //\r\n                // Let's go ahead and use the variable in the Translate call. \r\n\r\n                // OBJECTIVE: Move Player Left and Right with the User Input\r\n\r\n                // By multiplying everything by the <horizontalInput>, we allow the User to control the Player's movement.\r\n                // If <horizontalInput> is negative, it will actually move left instead of <right> because it will reverse the direction.\r\n                // When there is no user input, the <horizontalInput> will be 0 and the whole multiplication will become 0, so the player will not move.\r\n                // We now move our player in the <right> direction, controlled by the <horizontalInput>, with a speed of <playerSpeed>, in real-time by including <deltaTime>.\r\n\r\n                // Now the player will move left and right correctly.\r\n                // [Press the left and right keys (or A and D) to control the player.]\r\n                var __axis = \"Horizontal\";\r\n                var __speed = playerSpeed;\r\n                var __direction = Vector3.right;\r\n\r\n                if (Step.IsExperimentingHere)\r\n                {\r\n                    __axis = Step.ExperimentWith(__axis, \"Horizontal\", \"Vertical\");\r\n                    __speed = (step.IsAt(Steps.TranslateUpAndDown_GetVerticalInput))\r\n            {\r\n                // Now we can move left and right.\r\n                // We also need to move forward and backward. \r\n                //\r\n                // For the forward and backward movement, we will use the \"Vertical\" axis.\r\n                // The \"Vertical\" axis maps to the up and down arrow keys (or W and S for WASD input).\r\n                // \r\n                // Go ahead and try to store the Vertical input into a variable named verticalInput.\r\n\r\n                // OBJECTIVE: Get the <Vertical> Input value\r\n                // SEARCH: vertical input\r\n                // DOCS: http://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Input.GetAxis.html\r\n\r\n                // To get the <\"Vertical\"> input, we call the <GetAxis> method.\r\n                // The <\"Vertical\"> axis will be -1 for down (S key) and +1 for up (W key).\r\n\r\n                // Now we have the up and down input, but we have not used it yet.\r\n                float horizontalInput = Input.GetAxis(\"Horizontal\");\r\n                float verticalInput = Input.GetAxis(\"Vertical\");\r\n\r\n                transform.Translate(Vector3.right * horizontalInput * playerSpeed * Time.deltaTime);\r\n            }\r\n\r\n            if (step.IsAt(Steps.TranslateUpAndDown_UseVerticalInput))\r\n            {\r\n                // Now we have the value of the vertical input.\r\n                // We need to use that value to control the forward and backward movement of the Player.\r\n                //\r\n based on up and down input.\r\n                // [Press Up and Down (W and S) to control the forward and backward movement.]\r\n                var __speed = playerSpeed;\r\n\r\n                if (Step.IsExperimentingHere)\r\n                {\r\n                    __speed = Step.ExperimentWith(__speed,\r\n                        playerSpeed, \"playerSpeed\", 5f, \"5f\", 1f, \"1f\", 2f, executed first, so we can still access the <y> and <z> of the old <position>. \r\n                // After the new <Vector3> is created then it will be assigned to the <position> property of the <transform> component.\r\n\r\n                // Now if the player moves beyond the right edge, it will immediately be transported to the left edge.\r\n                // [Move the player past the {"CodeSource":"using UnityEngine;\r\nusing System.Collections;\r\nusing System.Collections.Generic;\r\n\r\npublic class MovePlayerLaser : MonoBehaviour\r\n{\r\n    [DeclareMemberStep(Steps.DeclareLaserSpeedVariable)]\r\n    // We created the laser, but it is not moving yet.\r\n    //\r\n    // We must follow the same pattern that we used to Move the Player.\r\n    // First, we need to create a variable for the laser's speed.\r\n    // \r\n    // Declare a laserSpeed variable with the default value of 5;\r\n\r\n    // OBJECTIVE: Declare a variable called \"laserSpeed\" with the default value of \"5\"\r\n\r\n    // The <laserSpeed> is a <float> field and will have the default value of 5.\r\n\r\n    // Now we have a laserSpeed variable, but we do not use it yet.\r\n    public float laserSpeed = 5;\r\n\r\n    void Update()\r\n    {\r\n        if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.TranslatePlayerLaser)) { return; }\r\n        // We must translate the laser in a similar way that we moved the player.\r\n        // However, because its model is rotated differently, we will move it using the \"up\" direction.\r\n        //\r\n        // Let's translate the laser up with the correct laserSpeed.\r\n\r\n        // OBJECTIVE: Move the laser up using the laserSpeed.\r\n\r\n        // We move the laser <up> at <laserSpeed> using the <deltaTime> .\r\n\r\n        // Now the player laser is moving correctly.\r\n        // [Hit the space key to shoot a laser and see it move forward.]\r\n        var __direction = Vector3.up;\r\n        var __laserSpeed = laserSpeed;\r\n\r\n        if (Step.IsExperimentingHere)\r\n        {\r\n            __direction = Step.ExperimentWith(__direction,\r\n                Vector3.up, \"Vector3.up\", Vector3.down, \"Vector3.down\",\r\n                Vector3.right, \"Vector3.right\", Vector3.left, \"Vector3.left\",\r\n                Vector3.forward, \"Vector3.forward\", Vector3.back, \"Vector3.back\",\r\n                Vector3.zero, \"Vector3.zero\");\r\n\r\n            __laserSpeed = Step.ExperimentWith(__laserSpeed,\r\n                laserSpeed, \"laserSpeed\", 10f, \"10f\", 5f, \"5f\", 1f, \"1f\", 0f, \"0f\", -1f, \"-1f\", -1.5f, \"-1.5f\");\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        transform.Translate(__direction * __laserSpeed * Time.deltaTime);\r\n\r\n        if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.IfPlayerLaserIsBeyondScreen)) { return; }\r\n        // Our laser moves correctly, but it stays in the scene forever which could hurt game performance.\r\n        //\r\n        // OBJECTIVE: Declare a float variable named <enemySpawnerSpeed>\r\n\r\n    // The spawner will move at about <2f> meters per second which is the <enemySpawnerSpeed>.\r\n\r\n    // Now we have the speed for the enemy spawner.\r\n    // We will use this to control it's left and right movement.\r\n    public float enemySpawnerSpeed = 2f;\r\n\r\n method.\r\n\r\n                // Now the enemy spawner is moving towards the right.\r\n                // Notice that each new enemy starts further towards the right.\r\n                // [Move the player ship and notice that the enemy spawner will go beyond the right edge of the screen.]\r\n                transform.Translate(Vector3.right * enemySpawnerSpeed * Time.deltaTime);\r\n            }\r\n\r\n            if (step.IsAt(Steps.TranslateEnemySpawnerInTheCorrectDirection))\r\n            {\r\n                // Now that we have a direction variable, we need to use it. \r\n                //\r\n                // Use the enemySpawnerDirection in the Translate call.\r\n                // OBJECTIVE: Translate the Enemy Spawner using its Direction and Speed variables.\r\n\r\n                // The enemySpawner will move in the <enemySpawnerDirection>.\r\n\r\n                // Now the enemy spawner is moving according to the direction variable.\r\n                // It is still going towards the right, but now we can change the direction.\r\n                transform.Translate(enemySpawnerDirection * enemySpawnerSpeed * Time.deltaTime);\r\n            }\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.SwitchEnemySpawnerDirection_IfAtRightEdge_GoLeft)) { return; }\r\n        // Now the Translate call is using the direction variable, but we never actually change the direction.\r\n        // \r\n        // We need to make the enemy spawner switch directions when it gets to the edge of the screen.\r\n        //\r\n        // Check if the spawner has reached the right edge of the screen and switch its direction to left when it does.\r\n\r\n        // OBJECTIVE: Switch the spawner direction to the left whenever the enemy spawner reaches the x position of 10.\r\n\r\n        // When the enemySpawner reaches the right side of the screen (when <x> is greater than 10), it will start moving <left>.\r\n\r\n        // Now when the enemy spawner reaches the right side, it will change direction and go towards the left.\r\n        // [Move your ship around and watch how the enemy spawner changes direction.]\r\n        if (transform.position.x > 10)\r\n the direction when it reaches the right side, we need to do the same for the left.\r\n        //\r\n        // Check if the spawner has reached the left edge of the screen and switch its direction to right.\r\n\r\n        // OBJECTIVE: Switch the spawner direction to the right whenever the enemy spawner reaches the x position of -10.\r\n\r\n        // When the enemySpawner reaches the left side of {"CodeSource":"using UnityEngine;\r\nusing System.Collections;\r\nusing System.Collections.Generic;\r\n\r\npublic class SpawnEnemies : MonoBehaviour\r\n{\r\n    [HideMember]\r\n    // HIDEN\r\n    public void Awake()\r\n    {\r\n        Step.ChangeStep += (sender, e) =>\r\n        {\r\n            var enemies = FindObjectsOfType<MoveEnemy>();\r\n\r\n            foreach (var enemy in enemies)\r\n            {\r\n                if (enemy.transform.parent == null)\r\n                {\r\n                    Destroy(enemy.gameObject);\r\n                }\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    [DeclareMemberStep(Steps.DeclareEnemyPrefabVariable)]\r\n    // We need to create a variable to hold the gameObject we want to spawn. \r\n    // Name it \"enemyPrefab\". \r\n\r\n    // OBJECTIVE: Declare a variable to hold the enemyPrefab. \r\n\r\n    // The enemyPrefab is a <GameObject> .\r\n\r\n    // Now we have a gameObject variable that will hold the enemy prefab.\r\n    // We will use it to create the enemies.\r\n    public GameObject enemyPrefab;\r\n\r\n    [DeclareMemberStep(Steps.DeclareSpawnEnemyDelayVariable)]\r\n    // We want to spawn enemies about every 3 seconds.\r\n    // We will use a variable for that so that we can change it later if needed.\r\n\r\n    // OBJECTIVE: Declare a variable named spawnEnemyDelay\r\n\r\n    // A new enemy will be created every 3 seconds, which is the <spawnEnemyDelay>.\r\n\r\n    // Now we have a variable to control the time delay between enemy spawns.\r\n    // We will use it to control how often an enemy is created.\r\n    public float spawnEnemyDelay = 3f;\r\n\r\n    [DeclareMemberStep(Steps.DeclareTimeCanSpawnVariable)]\r\n    // Now let's create a variable to determine if we can spawn an enemy. \r\n    // this variable will be compared against how long the game has been running. \r\n\r\n    // OBJECTIVE: Create a private variable named <timeCanSpawn>.\r\n\r\n    // When the game time reaches <timeCanSpawn>, a new enemy will be created.\r\n\r\n    // Now we have a variable to keep track of the correct time to create a new enemy. \r\n    // We will use it to indicate when a new enemy can be spawned.\r\n    private float timeCanSpawn;\r\n\r\n    void Update()\r\n    {\r\n        if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.IfTimeBetweenEnemiesHasPassed)) { return; }\r\n\r\n        // What we are doing here is creating a cool down system.\r\n        // A cool down system works by comparing how long the game has been running against some variable, and if it's a true condition, you spawn an enemy, and then add a delay to the variable that was being compared. \r\n        //\r\n        // In order to complete this, we need to know how to get information about how long the game has been running. \r\n        // This can be done through the Time class in Unity. \r\n        // The Unity documentation on Time.time has a similar example.\r\n        //\r\n        // After however long the game has been running is greater than our timeCanSpawn value which is zero, you need to assign our canSpawn value to the current time of the game plus the added delay. \r\n\r\n        // OBJECTIVE: Create cool down system\r\n        // SEARCH: time\r\n        // DOCS: http://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Time-time.html\r\n\r\n        // The game time is the number of seconds since the game started and is stored in <Time>.time. \r\n        // We will spawn a new enemy when the game time reaches the <timeCanSpawn> time.\r\n\r\n        // Now we can check if it is time to create an enemy.\r\n        // However we have not actually done anything yet.\r\n        if (Time.time > timeCanSpawn)\r\n        {\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.InstantiateEnemy)) { return; }\r\n            // Let's instantiate our enemyPrefab at this gameObject's position. \r\n            // We need the rotation to be that of the prefab. Instead of using Quaternion.identity,\r\n            // You will need to use the rotation value of the enemyPrefab's rotation. \r\n\r\n            // OBJECTIVE: Instantiate enemyPrefab with enemyPrefab rotation\r\n\r\n            // To create an enemy we use the <Instantiate> method.\r\n            // We will create a new enemy by cloning the <enemyPrefab>.\r\n            // The new enemy will be at the same <position> as this EnemySpawner.\r\n            // The new enemy will have the same <rotation> as the enemyPrefab.\r\n\r\n            // Now we will see the enemy when it is created.\r\n            // However, it does not move or do anything yet.\r\n            Instantiate(enemyPrefab, transform.position, enemyPrefab.transform.rotation);\r\n\r\n\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.IfTimeBetweenEnemiesHasPassed_SetNextTime)) { return; }\r\n            // We created an enemy, but we need to update the timeCanSpawn so that we can create another enemy later.\r\n            //\r\n            // We want to spawn another enemy after the spawn delay.\r\n            //\r\n            // Set the timeCanSpawn variable to the next time that an enemy can be created.\r\n\r\n            // OBJECTIVE: Set the timeCanSpawn variable to the next Spawn Time\r\n\r\n            // The <timeCanSpawn> is the next time we will spawn an enemy.\r\n            // We add the <spawnEnemyDelay> to the current game <time> to get the time for the next enemy.\r\n\r\n            // Now a new enemy will be created every 3 seconds.\r\n            // However, the enemies do not move, so they are all at the exact same spot.\r\n            // It looks like there is only 1 enemy, but there are actually many in the same spot.\r\n            timeCanSpawn = Time.time + spawnEnemyDelay;\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n","NodeDataList":[{"NodeType":"CodeFileNode","NodeID":12511,"KindValue":1,"SourceCodeIndex":0,"SourceCodeLength":5443,"FileName":"SpawnEnemies.cs","CodeNodeReferences":[{"Key":"AllNodes","Value":[12361,11565,11567,11569,11572,12362,11576,12363,11580,12364,11584,11586,12365,11589,12366,11593,12367,11598,12368,11602,11604,12369,11607,12370,11612,12371,11616,11618,11620,12372,11623,12444,12359]}],"IntegerValues":[],"BooleanValues":[{"Key":"IsBlock","Value":false}]},{"NodeType":"CodeSimpleNode","NodeID":12361,"KindValue":18,"SourceCodeIndex":0,"SourceCodeLength":5,"FileName":null,"CodeNodeReferences":[],"IntegerValues":[],"BooleanValues":[]},{"NodeType":"CodeSimpleNode","NodeID":11565,"KindValue":13,"SourceCodeIndex":5,"SourceCodeLength":1,"FileName":null,"CodeNodeReferences":[],"IntegerValues":[],"BooleanValues":[]},{"NodeType":"CodeSimpleNode","NodeID":11567,"KindValue":17,"SourceCodeIndex":6,"SourceCodeLength":11,"FileName":null,"CodeNodeReferences":[],"IntegerValues":[],"BooleanValues":[]},{"NodeType":"CodeSimpleNode","NodeID":11569,"KindValue":14,"SourceCodeIndex":17,"SourceCodeLength":1,"FileName":null,"CodeNodeReferences":[],"IntegerValues":[],"BooleanValues":[]},{"NodeType":"CodeSimpleNode","NodeID":11572,"KindValue":13,"SourceCodeIndex":18,"SourceCodeLength":2,"FileName":null,"CodeNodeReferences":[],"IntegerValues":[],"BooleanValues":[]},{"NodeType":"CodeSimpleNode","NodeID":12362,"KindValue":18,"SourceCodeIndex":20,"SourceCodeLength":5,"FileName":null,"CodeNodeReferences":[],"IntegerValues":[],"BooleanValues":[]},{"NodeType":"CodeSimpleNode","NodeID":11576,"KindValue":13,"SourceCodeIndex":25,"SourceCodeLength":1,"FileName":null,"CodeNodeReferences":[],"IntegerValues":[],"BooleanValues":[]},{"NodeType":"CodeSimpleNode","NodeID":12363,"KindValue":21,"SourceCodeIndex":26,"SourceCodeLength":6,"FileName":null,"CodeNodeReferences":[],"IntegerValues":[],"BooleanValues":[]},{"NodeType":"CodeSimpleNode","NodeID":11580,"KindValue":14,"SourceCodeIndex": {"CodeSource":"using UnityEngine;\r\nusing System.Collections;\r\n\r\npublic class EnemyCollisions : MonoBehaviour\r\n{\r\n    [DeclareMemberStep(Steps.DeclareEnemyExplosionVariable)]\r\n    // PLACEHOLDER COMMENT\r\n    public GameObject enemyExplosion;\r\n\r\n    [DeclareMemberStep(Steps.DeclareEnemyCollisions_OnTriggerEnterMethod)]\r\n\r\n    // Here we will be declaring a method that will allow\r\n    // us to check if the player has collided with us (the enemy). \r\n    // When programming in behaviors, it's good practice\r\n    // to pretend you're the object being scripted. \r\n    // We are currently on the enemy and we are \r\n    // checking for a collision between the Player and us!\r\n\r\n    // Go ahead and create the method for triggered collisions. \r\n    // Store the object that collided with you in a variable named other. \r\n\r\n    // OBJECTIVE: Declare OnTriggerEnter method\r\n    // SEARCH: OnTriggerEnter\r\n    // DOCS: http://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/MonoBehaviour.OnTriggerEnter.html\r\n\r\n    // The <OnTriggerEnter> method allows us to react to a collision with a trigger.\r\n    // We can access the <Collider> that actually hit the enemy through the <other> variable.\r\n\r\n    // Now we have a method where we can handle enemy collisions.\r\n    // We will use it to destroy the enemy when it hits another object.\r\n    void OnTriggerEnter(Collider other)\r\n    {\r\n        if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.IfEnemyCollidedWithLaser)) { return; }\r\n        // Now that we are checking for triggered events,\r\n        // we need to check who exactly it is that collided with us.\r\n        // Remember, we are on the enemy script acting as the enemy. \r\n        // We are checking for a collision between the laser and us. \r\n\r\n        // Go ahead and check if the object that collided with us has a tag of \"Laser.\"\r\n\r\n        // OBJECTIVE: Check if the Laser Hit Us\r\n\r\n        // We must check if the <other> object that hit the enemy is a <\"Laser\">.\r\n        // We can label game objects with a <tag> to identify what role it has in the game logic. \r\n\r\n        // Now we can detect when a laser hits the enemy. \r\n        // However, nothing happens yet.\r\n        if (other.tag == \"Laser\")\r\n        {\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.RemoveEnemyAndLaser)) { return; }\r\n            // So what happens when the laser collides with us? \r\n            // Both objects should be destroyed. So how do we do this? \r\n            // Lucky for you, Unity provides a Destroy command that can\r\n            // be used to delete gameObjects. \r\n\r\n            // Try and figure out how to destroy both the laser and the enemy object.\r\n\r\n            // OBJECTIVE: Destroy the laser followed by the player Gameobject.\r\n            // SEARCH: Destroy\r\n            // DOCS: http://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Object.Destroy.html\r\n\r\n            // We will remove both the enemy <gameObject> and the laser gameObject with the <Destroy> method. \r\n            // The enemy <gameObject> that is attached to this script is <this>.gameObject.\r\n            // The laser gameObject that hit this enemy is the <other>.gameObject.\r\n\r\n            // Finally, the enemy will be destroyed by the laser,\r\n            // and the laser will disappear also.\r\n            // [Shoot the enemy with a laser to see them both disappear.]\r\n            Destroy(other.gameObject);\r\n            Destroy(gameObject);\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.ShowEnemyExplosion_CollidedWithLaser)) { return; }\r\n            // PLACEHOLDER COMMENT\r\n\r\n            // When we are hit by the laser, let's go ahead and add \r\n            // an enemy explosition. In order to create this effect,\r\n            // you will be instantiating the enemyExplosion at the enemy's position. \r\n\r\n            // Go ahead and instantiate the enemyExplosion at our position. \r\n            // Use a value of 0 for the rotation. (Quaternion.identity)\r\n\r\n            // OBJECTIVE: Instantiate enemyExplosion\r\n\r\n            // Check out the game preview to review the results. \r\n            Instantiate(enemyExplosion, transform.position, Quaternion.identity);\r\n\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.AddScore_DestoryEnemyWithLaser)) { return; }\r\n            // PLACEHOLDER COMMENT\r\n\r\n            ScoreAccess.Score += 100;\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.IfEnemyCollidedWithPlayer)) { return; }\r\n\r\n        // Now we can move onto creating an action for when the two collide.\r\n        // Before dealing with any action, it's wise to check who the \r\n        // collided object is. You can find information\r\n        // about the object that collided with you by accessing \r\n        // the variable <other> that stores the other objects collider.\r\n        // Through this variable, you can check any property on the object. \r\n\r\n        // Go ahead and check if we collided with the player.\r\n\r\n        // OBJECTIVE: Check if we collided with the player\r\n\r\n        // <other> is the variable that stores information about the gameObject who collided with us.\r\n        // the <tag> property is being checked to see if it matches <Player>.\r\n\r\n        // Now we check if the player hit the enemy. \r\n        // However, nothing happpens yet.\r\n        if (other.tag == \"Player\")\r\n        {\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.RemoveEnemy_ButNotPlayer)) { return; }\r\n            // PLACEHOLDER COMMENT\r\n\r\n            // Now that we are checking to see if we collided with the Player,\r\n            // It's time to destroy ourselves. \r\n\r\n            // OBJECTIVE: Destroy the enemy (us)\r\n            // SEARCH: Destroy\r\n            // DOCS: http://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/Object.Destroy.html\r\n\r\n            // The method used to Destroy objects is the <Destroy< method. \r\n            // the <this> key word specifies this object meaning the enemy (us)\r\n            // We have to type dot <gameObject> because we have to specify what we want to destroy. \r\n\r\n            // Now the enemy will disappear, but nothing happens to the player.\r\n            // [Move the player to hit an enemy and see the enemy disappear.]\r\n            Destroy(gameObject);\r\n\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.ShowEnemyExplosion_CollidedWithPlayer)) { return; }\r\n            // Just like before, let's go ahead and instantiate the enemyExplosion again.\r\n\r\n            // OBJECTIVE: Instantiate the enemyExplosion\r\n\r\n            // Test out the game in the preview mode to see the result. \r\n            Instantiate(enemyExplosion, transform.position, Quaternion.identity);\r\n        }\r\n\r\n\r\n        if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.NOT_DONE)) { return; }\r\n        // PLACEHOLDER COMMENT\r\n\r\n        // Let's do some more! What about checking\r\n        // for if we collide with an Astroid? \r\n\r\n        // Go ahead and check for a tag that matches\r\n        // the name Astroid. \r\n\r\n        // OBJECTIVE: Check Collision for Astroid\r\n\r\n        if (other.tag == \"Astroid\")\r\n        {\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.NOT_DONE)) { return; }\r\n            // If we hit the astroid, destroy us!\r\n\r\n            // OBJECTIVE: Destroy the enemy\r\n\r\n            // Test out the preview to view the results.\r\n            Destroy(gameObject);\r\n\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.NOT_DONE)) { return; }\r\n            // Last but not least, what do we do when we destroy the enemy?\r\n            // We include the enemyExplosion. \r\n\r\n            // Go ahead and instantiate the enemy explosion. \r\n\r\n            // OBJECTIVE: Instantiate enemyExplosion\r\n\r\n            // Review the completed tasks in the preview mode. \r\n            Instantiate(enemyExplosion, transform.position, Quaternion.identity);\r\n        }\r\n\r\n method just like we did for the Enemy.\r\n    // OBJECTIVE: Declare an OnTriggerEnter method to handle Player collisions.\r\n\r\n    // Any <Collider> that hits the player will be in the <other> variable.\r\n\r\n    // Now we have a method where we can handle player collisions.\r\n    // We will use it to damage the player when it hits another object.\r\n    public void OnTriggerEnter(Collider other)\r\n    {\r\n        if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.IfPlayerCollidedWithEnemy)) { return; }\r\n        // Not everything that collides with the player will damage it.\r\n        // \r\n        // In fact, the only thing that can damage the Player right now is an Enemy.\r\n        // So, we need to check if the other object is a part of an Enemy.\r\n        // \r\n        // Check the tag to verify that the other object is an \"Enemy\".\r\n        // OBJECTIVE: Check if the other Collider is an \"Enemy\"\r\n\r\n        // We check if the <other> collider belongs to an <\"Enemy\"> with the <tag> property.\r\n\r\n        // Now we can detect if an enemy hits the player.\r\n        // However, nothing happens to the player yet.\r\n        if (other.tag == \"Enemy\")\r\n        {\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.SetPlayerToInactive)) { return; }\r\n            // Now we must handle what happens when the Player is hit by the enemy.\r\n            //\r\n            // We want the player to disappear from the game and later we will restart the player with a new life.\r\n            // We don't want to destroy the player object because it is unique and we should reuse it.\r\n            //\r\n            // Use the SetActive method to hide the Player from the scene.\r\n            // OBJECTIVE: Make the Player Inactive to hide it from the scene.\r\n            // SEARCH: Make GameObject Inactive\r\n            // DOCS: http://docs.unity3d.com/ScriptReference/GameObject.SetActive.html\r\n\r\n            // We hide the player by making it inactive with the <SetActive> method.\r\n            // By passing <false> to the <SetActive> method, the player will no longer be visibile in the scene.\r\n            // The player <gameObject> will still exist in the scene and we can make it reappear by passing true to <SetActive>.\r\n\r\n            // Now the player will disappear when hit by an enemy.\r\n            // [Move the player to hit an enemy and see it disappear.]\r\n            gameObject.SetActive(false);\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.DisplayPlayerExplosion)) { return; }\r\n            // PLACEHOLDER COMMENT\r\n\r\n            Instantiate(playerExplosion, transform.position, Quaternion.identity);\r\n\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.InformGameRulesThatPlayerDied)) { return; }\r\n            // PLACEHOLDER COMMENT\r\n\r\n            GameRulesController.Instance.PlayerDied();\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.NOT_DONE)) { return; }\r\n        // PLACEHOLDER COMMENT\r\n\r\n        if (other.tag == \"Astroid\")\r\n        {\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.NOT_DONE)) { return; }\r\n            // PLACEHOLDER COMMENT\r\n\r\n {"CodeSource":"using UnityEngine;\r\nusing System.Collections;\r\nusing System.Collections.Generic;\r\n\r\npublic class ScrollBackground : MonoBehaviour\r\n{\r\n    [HideMember]\r\n    // HIDEN\r\n    private Vector3 _startPosition;\r\n\r\n    [HideMember]\r\n    // HIDEN\r\n    void Awake()\r\n    {\r\n        _startPosition = transform.position;\r\n\r\n        Step.ChangeStep += (sender, e) =>\r\n        {\r\n            transform.position = _startPosition;\r\n        };\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    [DeclareMemberStep(Steps.DeclareTileHeightVariable)]\r\n    // Now the background moves down, but it will eventually run out.\r\n    // \r\n    // We have constructed the background out of two tiles, so that whenever it moved down enough, we can shift it back up a whole tile.\r\n    // If we move it the correct amount, the player won't be able to see anything.\r\n    // \r\n    // We must shift the background up exactly the size of a single tile. \r\n    // We will declare a tileHeight variable to make it easy to set this value from the editor and set its default to 50f.\r\n\r\n    // OBJECTIVE: Declare a variable for the background tileHeight.\r\n\r\n    // The background is made of tiles that have a <tileHeight> of <50f> meters in the scene.\r\n\r\n    // Now we can set the height of the tile.\r\n    // We will use this to move the background the height of exactly one tile so it will be invisible to the user.\r\n    public float tileHeight = 50f;\r\n\r\n    [DeclareMemberStep(Steps.DeclareBackgroundSpeedVariable)]\r\n    // We want out background to scroll to make it look like the player is flying over it.\r\n    // We will use the Translate method like we used to move everything else.\r\n    // We will need a speed variable so that we can adjust the speed to make it look right.\r\n    //\r\n    // Declare a variable to control the scrolling speed of the background with the default speed of 4f.\r\n    // OBJECTIVE: Declare a float variable called <backgroundSpeed>\r\n\r\n    // The <backgroundSpeed> will control how fast the background scrolls.\r\n\r\n    // Now we have a variable to control the speed of the background.\r\n    // We will use this to to scroll the background.\r\n    public float backgroundSpeed = 4f;\r\n\r\n    void Update()\r\n    {\r\n        if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.TranslateBackground)) { return; }\r\n        // We will move the background with the Translate method like we used for everything else.\r\n        //\r\n        // Use the Translate method to make the background move down according to the backgroundSpeed.\r\n        // OBJECTIVE: Translate the Background down with the Speed variable.\r\n\r\n        // We scroll the background using the <Translate> method just like we moved everything else.\r\n        // The background is moving <down> at the <backgroundSpeed>.\r\n\r\n        // Now the background is moving down.\r\n        // The player looks like it is flying forward.\r\n        // [Keep moving the player around and notice how the background will eventually run out after many seconds.]\r\n        transform.Translate(Vector3.down * backgroundSpeed * Time.deltaTime);\r\n\r\n        if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.IfBackgroundPositionHasMovedDownAWholeTile_MoveBackUpATile)) { return; }\r\n        // Now we need to check if our background has moved down enough that we should shift it back up.\r\n        //\r\n        // Remember that our background is made out of 2 large identical tiles.\r\n        // When the top tile comes down far enough that it reaches the bottom tile's starting position,\r\n        // the background will look exactly the same as when the game first started.\r\n        // \r\n        // So, if we shift the background up at that time, the user will never see anything happen.\r\n        // Essentially, the bottom tile will be returning to its start position.\r\n        // \r\n        // We will repeat this process forever and the game will have an infinite scrolling background.\r\n        //\r\n        // Check if the background has moved the distance of an entire tile's height.\r\n        // OBJECTIVE: Check if the Background has Moved Below the tileHeight\r\n\r\n        // If the background <position> has moved down the distance of a <tileHeight> then it is ready to be moved back up.\r\n\r\n        // Now we can detect if the background has moved down far enough to move it back up a whole tile.\r\n        // However, we have not done anything yet.\r\n        if (transform.position.y < -tileHeight)\r\n        {\r\n            if (Step.IsBefore(Steps.MoveBackgroundUpTheHeightOfATile)) { return; }\r\n            // Now we have waited for the right time to shift the background, but we must shift it back up in a single frame.\r\n            //\r\n            // We can still use the Translate method, but we must not use Time.deltaTime, because the background must move the entire height at once.\r\n            //\r\n            // Translate the background back up using the tileHeight without using Time.deltaTime.\r\n            // OBJECTIVE: Translate the Background Up using the tileHeight\r\n\r\n            // To make the background move back up, we <Translate> it again.\r\n            // We do not use Time.deltaTime, because we must move the background <up> in a single frame to jump the whole length of its <tileHeight>.\r\n            // The user cannot notice if the background moves <up> using the <tileHeight> because each tile is the same.\r\n\r\n            // Now when the background moves down enough, we will move it up a whole tile.\r\n            // This will be invisible to the user, but it will make the game have an infinite scrolling background.\r\n            // [Keep moving the player around and notice that the background scrolls forever.]\r\n            transform.Translate(Vector3.up * tileHeight);\r\n        }\r\n
